Learning objectives for today

  • Learn about basic foundational principles of health informatics and record linkages processes
  • Develop an understanding of potential sources of bias resulting in poorly linked data such as relying on exact matches or failing to account for name homogeneity among sub-populations
  • Gain experience through worked example on how to use the R RecordLinkage package for linking data

Record linkage Overview

  • The process of matching records related to one individual across data systems. In Public health, we often do this for an entire well defined population.
    • Simplified when a unique identifer is shared and available between systems
    • Often based on a number of personal identifiers (e.g. name, dob, address, sex…)
    • Methods that score similarites/dissimilarties of identifiers are often needed.

Two broad aims of record integration

System Services

  • Improve client services between agencies
  • Improve referrals/follow-up
  • Understand client services utalization
  • Usually “real-time”

Population Assessment

  • Conduct etiologic, predictive and other assessments
  • Improve indicators and prevalence/incidence estimates
  • Broaden information to understand a public health issue
  • Usually “point-in-time”

Merge and record linkage

Merge

  • Joining two sources based on one or more common identifiers
    • Join types (left, right, inner, full, semi, anti)
    • left: matching rows from a to b
    • right: matching rows from b to a
    • inner: matching rows from a and b only
    • full: matching rows and columns from a or b
    • semi: all rows in a that match in b
    • anti: all rows in a that do no match in b

Linkage

  • Deterministic record linkage equivalent to merge
    • Values from input A = values from input B (0,1)
    • Simple
  • Probabalistic (Fuzzy) allows for variation between record sets
    • Uses same join functions depending on purpose of linkage
    • Values from input A approximatly = to values from input B (0:1)
    • Complex and more time consuming

General linkage steps

  1. Obtain data and organize (best to use common source type like CSV)
  2. Get to know data elements in sources (is blocking warranted)
  3. Clean & Standardize data elements used in linkage
  4. Establish linkage priorities (know your population)
  5. Determine linkage methods and thresholds
  6. Conduct linkage and manaul review
  7. Finalize and explore new data

General linkage diagram

Data cleaning and standardization

How much clearning is a product of your data, but convention suggests if using:

  • Distance algorithms minimal cleaning should occur
  • Soundex algorithms should involve removing special characters
  • Deterministic should involve a lot of data cleaning

In general:

  • Ensure each shared input identifier is in the same format e.g. date formatted the same, names split the same, character, numeric.
  • Ensure case is the same
  • Remove or subset prefixes and suffixes (e.g. Dr., Jr..)
  • Remove or align special characters (e.g. hyphenated last names and apostrophes)

Setting thresholds

Sensitivty and Specificity trade-off

Things to consider:

  • Longitudinal prospective cohort, missing a linkage (loss to follow-up) may be paramount.
  • Surveillance, balancing erroneous linkages and missed linkages.

Some helpful guidelines:

  • Use machine learning tools on a subset of data with manually reviewed known parameters.
  • Training datasets from your input sources can help establish sensitivity and specificity.
  • The generalized Petro Distribution can be leveraged to establish minimum thresholds.

Step 3: Record Linkage

At this point we're ready to start linking our data.

  • We're going to start with Deterministic linkages
    • Using uncleaned and cleaned data
  • We'll then conduct probabalistic matching
    • Using uncleaned and cleaned data

Within the linkage process we have multiple small considerations

  • more considerations with probabalistic matching -What fuzzy matching algorithm, thresholds, review standards…

Step 3.1: Deterministic Linkage

Lets first start with a simple exact match (merge) between these two datasets on multiple columns.

Deter.1<-merge(dat1,dat2,by=c("dob","lname","fname","sex"))
  length(rownames(Deter.1))

[1] 86

We have 100% specificity here but our sensitivity is only 86%. With a little cleaning we increase this to 89%.

#Removing punctuation and spaces
    dat1c<-dat1
    dat2c<-dat2
      dat1c$lname<-toupper(gsub("[[:punct:][:space:]]","",dat1c$lname))
      dat1c$fname<-toupper(gsub("[[:punct:][:space:]]", "",dat1c$fname))
      dat1c$sex<-toupper(dat1c$sex)

      dat2c$lname<-toupper(gsub("[[:punct:][:space:]]", "",dat2c$lname))
      dat2c$fname<-toupper(gsub("[[:punct:][:space:]]", "",dat2c$fname))
      dat2c$sex<-toupper(dat2c$sex)
Deter.1c<-merge(dat1c,dat2c,by=c("dob","lname","fname","sex")) 
   length(rownames(Deter.1c))

Step 3.2: Weights

We're going to use the epiWeights() function which operationalizes the EpiLink approach used by Contiero et al. in the EpiLink record linkage software.1

1) P. Contiero et al., The EpiLink record linkage software, in: Methods of Information in Medicine 2005, 44 (1), 66-71 link

Bootstrap based classification trees 

  classif.bs<-trainSupv(p.1,method="bumping")
  result.bs<-classifySupv(model=classif.bs,newdata=l2a)
    pairs.bs<-getPairs(result.bs,show="links",single.rows=T)    
    #Merge with Truth to evaluate
    m_bs<-merge(Truth,pairs.bs[,c(1,2,11,19)],by.x=c("ID","ID.1"),by.y=c("ID.1","ID.2"),all=T)
    m_bs$inPairs<-with(m_bs,ifelse(is.na(m_bs$id1),0,1))
    addmargins(table(m_bs$inPairs,m_bs$modification,useNA = "always"))

Wrap-up

  • Merging data on partial identifiers is critical
  • Move beyond exact matching
  • Modest effort can result in large improvements
